<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-03-02T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-03-02T23:00:00-05:00" n="94" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d94">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/1193</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SW1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Spencer</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-03-03T12:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">March 3,
                                            1918, noon</hi></date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 12.16 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p><persName>Palmer</persName><note n="1" xml:id="d94fn1"><persName>William Morgan Palmer</persName>, Vice
                                    Consul.</note> in Irkutsk telegraphs as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                    <p>On account of anarchy regulations all commercial transactions
                                        are impossible. War prisoners are armed and organized.
                                        Maximalists are showing great discontent at Chinese embargo.
                                        They fear intervention by Japan or the Allies but such
                                        intervention is desired by almost the entire population and
                                        appears to be very urgent. Maximalists have warned consuls
                                        and foreigners that the country will make reprisals in case
                                        of need.</p></quote></p>
                            <p>I have transmitted the above to <persName corresp="#p_KAAM1">Admiral
                                    Knight</persName> in Vladivostok and instructed Consul <persName corresp="#p_MCK1">Moser</persName> in Harbin to give the Admiral
                                all possible information from every point of view.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed><persName corresp="#p_SW1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Spencer</hi></persName></signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>